{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.02,0.46,0.14,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7367"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72358"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1536"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5583"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44836"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a discussion about an upcoming CT angiogram to investigate suspected mesenteric ischaemia. She has a history of a moderate allergic reaction to iodinated contrast media three years ago, when she developed severe vomiting and marked urticaria. She has a medical history of asthma and takes salbutamol as needed. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well, with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral prednisone premedication protocol","Proceed with contrast CT without premedication","Intravenous hydrocortisone sodium succinate premedication protocol","Change to non-contrast CT scan","Conventional angiography"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires CT angiography to investigate suspected mesenteric ischaemia, which absolutely requires iodinated contrast media for vessel visualisation. She has a history of a moderate radiocontrast media hypersensitivity reaction, which puts her at increased risk for future reactions. The presence of asthma is an additional risk factor for contrast reactions as atopic individuals have a predisposition to developing an allergy. In these cases, alternative modalities should be considered, particularly where iodinated contrast media can be avoided. A discussion with the radiologist and immunologist would also be helpful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging to a non-contrast CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as CT angiography requires contrast enhancement to visualise the mesenteric vessels. A non-contrast scan would not answer the clinical question.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConventional angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is more invasive than CT angiography and still requires iodinated contrast media, so it would not avoid the risk of contrast reaction. Additionally, it carries risks associated with arterial puncture and catheterisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, premedication with corticosteroids and a non-sedating antihistamine may be helpful before receiving iodinated contrast media. \u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisone premedication protocol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. The standard protocol involves oral prednisone 50 mg at 13 hours, 7 hours, and 1 hour before contrast administration, often with the addition of a non-sedating antihistamine 1 hour prior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone sodium succinate premedication\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred option for elective imaging. While intravenous steroids may be used in emergencies where urgent imaging is required within 5 hours, oral prednisone is preferred for planned procedures as it allows adequate time for the medication to take effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceeding with contrast CT without premedication\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate, given her history of a moderate reaction. The risk of a repeat reaction is significant and could be more severe than the initial reaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alternative imaging modalities should be considered in patients with previous moderate to severe hypersensitivity reactions to contrast media.","If contrast media is absolutely required, premedication with corticosteroids and a non-sedating antihistamine may be helpful.","Oral prednisone may be used for non-urgent imaging, whereas hydrocortisone sodium succinate may be used for urgent imaging."],"references":["ASCIA Radiocontrast Media Hypersensitivity - Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA) [Internet]. [cited 2025 Mar 2]. Available from: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/drug-allergy/radiocontrast-media","Hsieh C, Wu SC, Kosik RO, Huang YC, Chan WP. Pharmacological Prevention of Hypersensitivity Reactions Caused by Iodinated Contrast Media: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Diagnostics (Basel). 2022 Jul 9;12(7):1673.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9320945/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72358"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T13:22:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T13:23:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7367"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88169"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":nul